        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Worthie Pescenninus tooke exceptions to the vntrained &amp; vnexercised youth of Scipio: but might not iust exception be taken to his 
                        fading &amp; drouping age: when right magnanimitie, &amp; pollicie might haue made him admirable? His frend Masinissa, &amp; his aduersarie 
                        Cato, atchieued great actions, when they were mutch elder, then Scipio was, when he dyed. Which may seeme to die in the melancholie 
                        moode of a drouping Malcontent. A base end for so braue A captaine, &amp; so worthie a man.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Pescennius Niger"/> <!-- LS, 135-194 AD -->
                <person name="Scipio Africanus"/> <!-- LS, 236-183 BC -->
                <person name="Masanissa"/> <!-- LS, 240-148 BC -->
                <person name="Cato the Elder"/> <!-- LS, 234-149 BC -->
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
